# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aboriginal-dugout-canoe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The second question of the 1967 Australian referendum of 27 May 1967, called by the Holt government, related to Indigenous Australians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked whether to give the Commonwealth Parliament the power to make special laws for Indigenous Australians, and whether Indigenous Australians should be included in official population counts for constitutional purposes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The term "the Aboriginal Race" was used in the question.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Technically the referendum question was a vote on the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginals) 1967 that would amend section 51(xxvi) and repeal section 127.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendments to the Constitution were overwhelmingly endorsed, winning 90.77% of votes cast and having majority support in all six states.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment became law on 10 August 1967.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1901, the attorney-general, Alfred Deakin, provided a legal opinion on the meaning of section 127 of the Constitution of Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 excluded "aboriginal natives" from being counted when reckoning the numbers of the people of the commonwealth or a state.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] His legal advice was that "half-castes" were not "aboriginal natives".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Prior to 1967, censuses asked a question about Aboriginal race to establish numbers of "half-castes" and "full-bloods".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] "Full-bloods" were then subtracted from the official population figure in accordance with the legal advice from the attorney-general.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Strong activism by individuals and both Indigenous and non-Indigenous groups greatly aided the success of the 1967 referendum in the years leading up to the vote.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Calls for Aboriginal issues to be dealt with at the federal level began as early as 1910.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From here, the overall plight of Aboriginal Australians became a fundamental political issue.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 7 April 1965, the Menzies Cabinet decided that it would seek to repeal section 127 of the Constitution at the same time as it sought to amend the nexus provision, but made no firm plans or timetable for such action.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In August 1965, attorney-general Billy Snedden proposed to Cabinet that abolition of section 127 was inappropriate unless section 51(xxvi) was simultaneously amended to remove the words "other than the aboriginal race in any state".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] He was rebuffed, but gained agreement when he made a similar submission to the Holt Cabinet in 1966.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the meantime, his Liberal colleague Billy Wentworth had introduced a private member's bill proposing *inter alia* to amend section 51(xxvi).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1964, the Leader of the Opposition, Arthur Calwell, had proposed such a change and pledged that his party, the Australian Labor Party, would back any referendum to that effect.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1967, the Australian Parliament was unanimous in voting for the alteration bill.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked to approve, together, changes to two provisions in the Constitution section 51(xxvi) and section 127.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] And the extraordinary clauses that follow (ordinarily referred to as heads of power) list most of the legislative powers of the federal parliament.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment gave the Commonwealth parliament power to make "special laws" with respect to Aboriginal People living in a state; the parliament already had unfettered power in regard to territories under section 122 of the Constitution.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Constitution required the calculation of "the people" for several purposes in sections 24, 89, 93 and 105.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 89 related to the imposition of uniform customs duties and operated until 1901.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 93 related to uniform custom duties after being imposed by section 89 and operated until 1908.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 105 related to taking over state debts and was superseded by section 105A inserted in the Constitution in 1929 following the 1928 referendum.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Accordingly, in 1967, only section 24 in relation to the House of Representatives had any operational importance to section 127.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 24 "requires the membership of the House of Representatives to be distributed among the States in proportion to the respective numbers of their people".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The number of people in section 24 is calculated using the latest statistics of the Commonwealth which are derived from the census.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 51(xi) of the Constitution enabled the Parliament to make laws for "census and statistics" and it exercised that power to pass the *Census and Statistics Act 1905*.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] At this time, territorians, while able and required to vote in elections, were not permitted to vote in referendums.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is frequently stated that the 1967 referendum gave Aboriginal people Australian citizenship and that it gave them the right to vote in federal elections; however, this was not the case.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1944, Aboriginal people in Western Australia could apply to become citizens of the state, which gave them various rights, including the right to vote.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This citizenship was conditional on adopting "the manner and habits of civilised life" and not associating with Aboriginal people other than their parents, siblings, children, or grandchildren, and could be taken away at any time.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Most Indigenous Australians continued to be denied the right to vote in elections for the Australian Parliament even after 1949.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The *Commonwealth Electoral Act 1962* gave all Aboriginal people the option of enrolling to vote in federal elections.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was not until the *Commonwealth Electoral Amendment Act 1983* that voting became compulsory for Aboriginal people, as it was for other Australians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Aboriginal people (and all other people) living in the Northern Territory were not allowed to vote in the referendum, which remained the case for both the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory until the Constitutional amendment to section 128 after a referendum in 1977.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is also sometimes mistakenly stated that the 1967 referendum overturned a Flora and Fauna Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This is believed to have come from the New South Wales *National Parks and Wildlife Act* 1974, which controlled Aboriginal heritage, land and culture.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The other states had equivalent acts which were managed by various departments, including those relating to agriculture and fishing.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 prevented the inclusion of the Indigenous Australians in the official population for constitutional purposes, i.e. their population would not be included in the calculation of the number of seats to assign for each state or in the determination of tax revenue.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The section did not prevent the Bureau of Statistics from counting or collecting other information about Indigenous Australians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1911 to 1966 the Bureau had collected information about Indigenous Australians, however this was published separately to the general population.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Inclusion in the general population was thus important symbolically, but the change did not directly improve the information available to government.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Ninety percent of voters voted yes, and the overwhelming support gave the Federal Government a clear mandate to implement policies to benefit Aboriginal people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Many misconceptions have arisen as to the outcomes of the referendum, some as a result of it taking on a symbolic meaning during a period of increasing Aboriginal self-confidence.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was some five years before any real change occurred as a result of the referendum, but federal legislation has since been enacted covering land rights, discriminatory practices, financial assistance, and preservation of cultural heritage.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was the intention of the government and many voters that this new power was to be only used beneficially.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, in the 1998 case of *Kartinyeri v Commonwealth*, the High Court did not find that such a restriction on the power existed, with the court being split 2:2 (2 judges not deciding) as to whether or not the power could be used to the *detriment* of an identified race.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy and the Northern Territory Intervention are two circumstances where the post-1967 race power has arguably been used in this way.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The 1967 referendum has acquired a symbolic meaning in relation to a period of rapid social change during the 1960s.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, it has been credited with initiating political and social change that was the result of other factors.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The real legislative and political impact of the 1967 referendum has been to enable, and thereby compel, the federal government to take action in the area of Aboriginal Affairs.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Federal governments with a broader national and international agenda have attempted to end the discriminatory practices of state governments such as Queensland and to introduce policies that encourage self-determination and financial security for Aboriginal people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, the effectiveness of these policies has been tempered by an unwillingness of most federal governments to deal with the difficult issues involved in tackling recalcitrant state governments.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It has been argued that Holt, who died not long after the referendum, was setting up a more extensive government response than Gorton enacted.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The benefits of the referendum began to flow to Aboriginal people in 1972.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 26 January 1972, Aboriginal peoples erected the *Aboriginal Tent Embassy* on the lawns of the Federal Parliament building in Canberra to express their frustration at the lack of progress on land rights and racial discrimination issues.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This became a major confrontation that raised Aboriginal affairs high on the political agenda in the federal election later that year.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One week after gaining office, the Whitlam government (1972–1975) established a Royal Commission into land rights for Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory under Justice Woodward.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The recommendations were framed in terms to enable application outside the Northern Territory.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The following year, the Fraser government (1975–1983) amended the Aboriginal Land (Northern Territory) Bill by introducing the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Bill.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This bill was passed as the *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976*.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is significant however that this legislation was implemented at all, given the political allegiances of the Fraser government, and shows the level of community support for social justice for Aboriginal people at the time.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government used its constitutional powers to overrule racially discriminatory state legislation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On reserves in Queensland, Aboriginal people were forbidden to gamble, use foul language, undertake traditional cultural practices, indulge in adultery, or drink alcohol.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] They were also required to work without payment.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Aboriginal Courts in Queensland the same official acted as judge as well as the prosecuting counsel.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Defendants almost invariably pleaded guilty as pleas of not guilty were more than likely to lead to a longer sentence.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government, using the race power, enacted the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders (Queensland Discriminatory Laws) Act 1975* to override the state laws and eliminate racial discrimination against Aboriginal people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, no federal government ever enforced this Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power was also used by the Whitlam government to introduce affirmative action in favour of Aboriginal people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It established schemes whereby Aboriginal people could obtain housing, loans, emergency accommodation and tertiary education allowances.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It also increased funding for the Aboriginal Legal Service enabling twenty-five offices to be established throughout Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power gained in the 1967 referendum has been used in several other pieces of significant Federal legislation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One of the pieces of legislation enacted to protect the Gordon River catchment used the race power but applied it to all people in Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The law prohibited anyone from damaging sites, relics and artefacts of Aboriginal settlement in the Gordon River catchment.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Tasmanian Dam Case, the High Court held that even though this law applied to all people and not only to Aboriginal people, it still constituted a special law.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the 1992 Mabo judgment, the High Court of Australia established the existence of Native Title in Australian Common Law.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Using the race power, the Keating Government enacted the *Native Title Act 1993* and successfully defended a High Court challenge from the Queensland Government.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In granting the Commonwealth a broad power to legislate in regards to Indigenous Australians, responsibilities for areas traditionally the purview of the states (such as housing, education and healthcare) was shared between both branches of government.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, both levels have sought to blame the other for the continuing disadvantage of Indigenous Australians, while seeking to place the cost and responsibility to manage these issues on the other.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] When John Howard's Coalition government came to power in 1996, it intervened in the Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy in South Australia with legislation that introduced an exception to the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Heritage Protection Act 1984*, to allow the bridge to proceed.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The High Court decided, by a majority, that the amended s.51(xxvi) of the Constitution still allowed the Commonwealth parliament to make laws either for the benefit or to the detriment of a particular race.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The **Aboriginal Areas Protection Authority** (**AAPA**) is an independent statutory authority established under the ***Northern Territory Aboriginal Sacred Sites Act 1989***.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Its function is to protect Aboriginal sacred sites within the Northern Territory of Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The 1989 act originated in a 1977 bill, signed into law as the *Aboriginal Sacred Sites Ordinance 1978* in November 1978, soon after the NT achieved self-government, and the **Aboriginal Sacred Sites Authority** was created.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The legislation became a subject of controversy among developers, the Northern Territory Government and the new authority.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Numerous amendments were proposed and debated, including its compatibility with the *Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Act 1976* (Cth), before the *Northern Territory Aboriginal Sacred Sites Act 1989* was passed on 26 May 1989, coming into force on 15 August 1989.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] This act created the Aboriginal Areas Protection Authority, which included new functions and expanded its work, and also introduced various measures to increase accountability.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] AAPA works with traditional owners to record "sites of physical, spiritual and cultural significance" on its Register of Sacred Sites.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Prospective land developers are legally obliged to apply for an Authority Certificate through AAPA.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] It is governed by a board of 12 people, mostly senior Aboriginal custodians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The authority board is made up of two members appointed by the NT Government, and five male and five female Aboriginal custodians nominated by the four NT Aboriginal Land Councils.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The ***Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Act 1976*** (**ALRA**) is Australian federal government legislation that provides the basis upon which Aboriginal Australian people in the Northern Territory can claim rights to land based on traditional occupation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It was the first law by any Australian government that legally recognised the Aboriginal system of land ownership, and legislated the concept of inalienable freehold title, as such was a fundamental piece of social reform.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Its long title is ***An Act providing for the granting of Traditional Aboriginal Land in the Northern Territory for the benefit of Aboriginals, and for other purposes***.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Act has been amended 27 times between 1978 and 2021.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The results of the 1967 Australian referendum meant that the Federal Government could make special laws relating to Aboriginal people which could override any state-based legislation; this was seen as a great victory in the struggle for Aboriginal land rights in Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Labor government under Gough Whitlam, after making land rights one of his election campaign priorities, first introduced a land rights Bill to Parliament.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Whitlam chose to establish a precedent in the Northern Territory (NT), which was controlled by the Commonwealth (federal) government, rather than attempt federal legislation first off.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] He appointed Justice Woodward in February 1973 to head an inquiry into how best to recognise Aboriginal land rights in the NT, called the Aboriginal Land Rights Commission (also known as the "Woodward Royal Commission").
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Woodward produced his final report in April 1974, expressing the opinion that one of the main aims of land rights was "The doing of simple justice to a people who have been deprived of their land without their consent and without compensation".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] He said that Aboriginal land should be granted as inalienable freehold title, meaning "it could not be acquired, sold, mortgaged or disposed of in any way", and title should be communal.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Bill lapsed upon the dismissal of the government in 1975.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Liberal government, led by Malcolm Fraser, reintroduced a similar Bill, and this was signed by the Governor-General of Australia on 16 December 1976.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It was the first law by any Australian government that legally recognised the Aboriginal system of land ownership, legislating the concept of inalienable freehold title, and thus the first of all Aboriginal land rights legislation in Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] *The Land Rights Act* is a fundamental piece of social reform.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It established the legal basis on which Aboriginal people could claim rights to land based on customary or traditional occupation, also known as native title, if evidence could be shown.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The main purpose of the Act is "to reinstate ownership of traditional Aboriginal land in the Northern Territory to Aboriginal people" (Austrade).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It provides for the grant of inalienable freehold title for Aboriginal land, meaning that the land cannot be bought or otherwise acquired, including by any NT law.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] In the original Act, only claims to unalienated Crown land in the NT were permissible, under three district sections, and the Act specified an end date of June 1997 by which claims had to be lodged.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Act allows for a claim of Australian native title if claimants can provide evidence of their traditional association with land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] About 50% of the Northern Territory land and 85% of its coastline are owned communally by Aboriginal peoples.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Since 1976, many amendments to the Act have been passed.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] As of July 2020, the most recent compilation (No.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Aboriginal Land Trusts are established under the Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Title to the land granted under the Act is held by these land trusts; as of 2020, there are 151 Aboriginal land trusts, each administered by a land council, dependent on location of the trust.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Act specified that at least two Land Councils must be created.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Central Land Council, covering the southern part of the NT, and the Northern Land Council, covering the northern part of the NT, were created by the Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Tiwi Land Council, covering Bathurst and Melville Islands north of Darwin, and the Anindilyakwa Land Council, covering Groote Eylandt and Bickerton Island in the Gulf of Carpentaria, were later created from parts of the Northern Land Council.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] New Land Councils can be created under the Act: Section 23 of the Act specifies the functions of Land Councils; however, the four original land councils continue to exist as of 2020.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Land development, including exploration and mining activities, on Aboriginal land are undertaken through negotiations with traditional owners groups and facilitated by land councils.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Various types of payment for the land, other financial and non-financial benefits may be included in negotiations.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The Act prescribes how the land councils and land trusts may grant usage rights and access, but in some circumstances a federal or NT Minister's approval is also required.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Income received for the use of the land is distributed by the land councils according to the agreements with the traditional owners and as the Act provides.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Royalties paid to the NT and Federal governments for the use of the land are processed and directed to the Aboriginals Benefit Account (ABA) (Part VI of the Act) and the funds are to be used for certain purposes prescribed by the Act which benefit Aboriginal peoples in the NT.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Section 69 (under "Part VII - Miscellaneous") of the Act defines a special category of land, the sacred site, which is a site of significance according to Aboriginal tradition.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It prohibits a person from entering a sacred site, with penalties of a fine or prison sentence.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] A significant review of the Act (referred to as ALRA) was undertaken from October 1997, when the government appointed barrister John Reeves to examine its effectiveness, operation of aspects relating to mining and the Aboriginal Benefits Trust Account, and the role of the Land Councils.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The *Reeves Report* concluded that the ALRA had been very effective in granting traditional Aboriginal land in the NT, with benefits exceeding their costs for the Aboriginal people, but it also made many recommendations for change.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Over some years, the issue of private versus communal ownership of Aboriginal land was considered and debated by many parties, including Warren Mundine, Mick Dodson, Galarrwuy Yunupingu, Noel Pearson and others.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Tom Calma, as Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Social Justice Commissioner, said in his *Native Title Report 2005* that it was "not necessary to put the communal tenure of Indigenous land at risk" by converting to individual freehold titles.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] It was agreed that there were benefits in the new proposals, but various details were debated at length.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Following the Government making changes to the ALRA in 2005, Australians for Native Title and Reconciliation expressed concern about Land Council funding and function changes and the establishment of new Land Councils.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] On 17 August 2006, the Howard government amended the Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The *Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Amendment Bill 2006*, in effect from 1 July 2007, added several clauses to the Act.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] The most significant amendments enabled Aboriginal groups to more directly manage their land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] Two Land Councils (Central and Northern) manage manage mainland NT Aboriginal land.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] By comparison, New South Wales has 121 Land Councils.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-land-rights-act-1976] These new sections of the Act included Section 19a, which introduced the option of Township Leasing, and Section 28a, which introduced the option of a 'delegation of powers' to a local Aboriginal corporation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Many Aboriginal community-controlled health services (ACCHSs) were subsequently founded across Australia, following the AMS model.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] At the time of the foundation of the AMS, there was no universal health care in Australia, such as Medicare provides today.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The foundation of the AMS was driven by Mum (Shirl) Smith, Dulcie Flower, Ken Brindle and Chicka and Elsa Dixon.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Fred Hollows, Dr Archie Kalokerinos, Dulcie Flower, and others, who were all concerned with the serious health problems of Aboriginal Australians in Sydney.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Its growth was encouraged by Redfern parish priest Fr Ted Kennedy.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The Sisters of Mercy donated the property in which the Aboriginal Medical Service had been established to the Redfern Aboriginal community in 1978.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Architect Col James, who did much work pro bono for various Aboriginal organisations, especially the Aboriginal Housing Company , also did work for the AMS.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Hollows recruited medical students, doctors and volunteers.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Founders also included Paul Coe, Dulcie Flower, John Russell, and Ross McKenna.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Aboriginal journalist John Newfong was the inaugural director, and Andrew Refshauge the chief medical practitioner.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Naomi Mayers joined as secretary in 1972, later becoming CEO.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Inspired by the success of the Aboriginal Legal Service in providing free services to the Aboriginal community, the group applied for a government grant, and opened the service in a shopfront in Regent Street, Redfern.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Its structure mirrored the Aboriginal Legal Service, with prominent community members acting as field officers and white professionals donating their time.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The service was controlled by Aboriginal people.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Its popularity was so great that it soon became unable to meet the demand for services.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] While the New South Wales Department of Aboriginal Affairs appeared committed to the service at first, the organisation struggled for secure funding during its first five years of operation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The department regularly delayed its assessment of funding applications, acquittals and payments, forcing the organisation to operate on bank overdrafts and donations from the community.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The centre was staffed by volunteers, and doctors brought their own equipment to use.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Despite this, the AMS provided all services free, with the option to donate if the patient felt able.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The struggle for funds continued for around 15 years.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The service employed a holistic approach to health care from the beginning.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Aboriginal health issues were viewed within the paradigm of Indigenous people's social, economic and political status in Australian society, and it was considered necessary to address this disadvantage in order to improve Aboriginal health.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The underlying agenda of the service was political in that it sought to enable Aboriginal people to control their own destinies.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The AMS, in association with Sol Bellear, Paul Coe, Mum Shirl, and Kaye Edwards, set up a breakfast program for children in a park in Newtown, serving food from a caravan borrowed from the Wayside Chapel.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] In 1977 the service moved to newly renovated premises in Turner Street, Redfern.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] A variety of specialist clinics were offered, as well as a general practice and dental clinic.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Dulcie Flower developed the first Aboriginal health workers (AHWs) course in 1984 at Redfern, and the AMS soon afterwards started running post-graduate course in mental health care.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] These later moved to educational institutions.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] At some time before 2012, the Aboriginal Medical Service changed its name to AMS Redfern.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The Aboriginal Medical Service inspired Aboriginal communities across the country to establish their own medical services, and by 2008 there were over 60 Aboriginal-controlled health services in the state of New South Wales.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] By 2012, there were 150 Aboriginal community-controlled health services (ACCHSs), following the AMS model, in urban, regional and remote Australia.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] In 2012, Naomi Mayers was CEO of the organisation.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] By this time, AMS had grown into a multidisciplinary health service, comprising a broad range of services and clinics.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] Apart from general medical, these included dental clinics, public health programs, and outreach services.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] It was also operating as a teaching practice, employing registrars and providing short-term placements for medical and nursing students from the University of Sydney.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] A number of hospitals and other organisations also collaborated with AMS.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The modern centre was designed by Merrima company, and built on the donated land adjacent to the St Vincent's Roman Catholic community including the church, presbytery, convent and school built around 1887.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] On 26 November 2022, the AMS held a gala dinner to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the AMS.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] As of 2022, AMS Redfern, registered as Aboriginal Medical Service Cooperative Limited, describes itself as a "multi-functional non-for-profit organisation that delivers a broad range of services and community programs".
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/aboriginal-medical-service] The joint CEOs are LaVerne Bellear and Aunty Dulcie Flower.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:aboriginal-dugout-canoe/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
